Humans comprise about 100 million tonnes of the Earth's dry biomass,<ref>The world [[human population]] was 6.6 billion in January 2008. At an average weight of 100 pounds (30 lbs of biomass), that equals 100 million tonnes.{{clarify| For this value, more than 7b people are needed in my calculation. And the wet biomass "420Mt" claim doesn't fit to this either|date=April 2012}}</ref> [[domesticate]]d animals about 700 million tonnes, [[earthworms]] over 1,100 million tonnes,<ref name=Blakemore2017 /> and annual cereal [[agriculture|crops]] about 2.3 billion tonnes.<ref>FAO Statistical Yearbook 2013: page 130 - http://www.fao.org/docrep/018/i3107e/i3107e.PDF</ref>

The most successful [[animal]] species, in terms of biomass, may well be [[Antarctic krill]], ''Euphausia superba'', with a fresh biomass approaching 500 million [[tonne]]s,<ref name="KrillBiomass2009">{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1016/j.dsr.2008.12.007 | vauthors = Atkinson A, Siegel V, Pakhomov EA, Jessopp MJ, Loeb V | year = 2009 | title = A re-appraisal of the total biomass and annual production of Antarctic krill | journal = Deep-Sea Research Part I | volume = 56 | pages = 727–740 | url = http://www.iced.ac.uk/documents/Atkinson%20et%20al,%20Deep%20Sea%20Research%20I,%202009.pdf | postscript = <!-- Bot inserted parameter. Either remove it; or change its value to "." for the cite to end in a ".", as necessary. --> | issue = 5 | bibcode = 2009DSRI...56..727A }}</ref><ref name="NE97"/><ref>Ross, R. M. and Quetin, L. B. (1988). Euphausia superba: a critical review of annual production. Comp. Biochem. Physiol. 90B, 499-505.</ref> although domestic cattle may also reach these immense figures.{{Citation needed|date=September 2011}} However, as a group, the small aquatic [[crustacean]]s called [[copepod]]s may form the largest animal biomass on earth.<ref name=Ossietzky>{{cite web|url=http://www.uni-oldenburg.de/zoomorphology/Biology.html|title=Biology of Copepods |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090101205840/http://www.uni-oldenburg.de/zoomorphology/Biology.html |archive-date=1 January 2009 |publisher=[[Carl von Ossietzky University of Oldenburg]]|author=|date=|website=uni-oldenburg.de}}</ref> A 2009 paper in ''Science'' estimates, for the first time, the total world fish biomass as somewhere between 0.8 and 2.0 billion tonnes.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Wilson RW, Millero FJ, Taylor JR, Walsh PJ, Christensen V, Jennings S, Grosell M | title = Contribution of fish to the marine inorganic carbon cycle | journal = Science | volume = 323 | issue = 5912 | pages = 359–62 | date = January 2009 | pmid = 19150840 | doi = 10.1126/science.1157972 | url = http://www.sciencemag.org/cgi/content/abstract/323/5912/359 | bibcode = 2009Sci...323..359W }}</ref><ref>[http://www.physorg.com/news151251277.html Researcher gives first-ever estimate of worldwide fish biomass and impact on climate change] ''[[PhysOrg.com]]'', 15 January 2009.</ref> It has been estimated that about 1% of the global biomass is due to [[phytoplankton]],<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Bidle KD, Falkowski PG | title = Cell death in planktonic, photosynthetic microorganisms | journal = Nature Reviews. Microbiology | volume = 2 | issue = 8 | pages = 643–55 | date = August 2004 | pmid = 15263899 | doi = 10.1038/nrmicro956 | url = http://www.nature.com/nrmicro/journal/v2/n8/abs/nrmicro956.html }}</ref> and 25% is due to [[fungi]].<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Miller | first1 = JD | year = 1992 | title = Fungi as contaminants in indoor air | url = http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0960168692904049 | journal = Atmospheric Environment | volume = 26 | issue = 12| pages = 2163–2172 | doi=10.1016/0960-1686(92)90404-9|bibcode = 1992AtmEn..26.2163M }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Sorenson WG | title = Fungal spores: hazardous to health? | journal = Environmental Health Perspectives | volume = 107 Suppl 3 | issue = Suppl 3 | pages = 469–72 | date = June 1999 | pmid = 10423389 | pmc = 1566211 | doi = 10.1289/ehp.99107s3469 | format = PDF }}</ref>

