'''Dendi''' is a [[Songhay language]] used as a [[trade language]] across northern [[Benin]] (along the [[Niger River]]; [[Donga Department|Donga]] and [[Alibori]] provinces, e.g. [[Djougou]], [[Kandi, Benin|Kandi]]). It forms a [[dialect cluster]] with [[Zarma language|Zarma]] and [[Koyraboro Senni|Songhai proper]] but is heavily influenced by [[Bariba language|Bariba]].

Dendi has been described as a four-[[Tone (linguistics)|tone]] language.<ref>Joe Salmons, ''Accentual change and language contact: Comparative survey and a case study of early Northern Europe''</ref>

