{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}} {{Use Indian English|date=August 2016}} {{BLP sources|date=July 2016}} {{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] --> | honorific-prefix = '''[[Doctor of philosophy|Dr.]]''' | name = Siddalingaiah | image = | imagesize = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = 1954 | birth_place = [[Magadi]], [[Bangalore]], India | death_date = | death_place = | occupation = Poet, dramatist, legislator and Dalit activist | nationality = Indian | citizenship = | education = Ph.D in Kannada | alma_mater = [[Bangalore University]] | period = | genre = | subjects = | movement = Dalit-[[Bandaya movement]] | notableworks = ''Holemadigara Haadu'', 1975 | spouse = | partner = | children = | relatives = | awards = | signature = }}
'''Siddalingaiah''' (born 1954, [[Magadi]], [[Bangalore]]) is an Indian poet and playwright writing in the [[Kannada]] language, and a [[Dalit]] activist and politician. He is credited with starting the Dalit-[[Bandaya movement]] in Kannada and with starting the genre of [[Dalit literature|Dalit writing]]. He is one of the founders of the Dalita Sangharsh Samiti along with [[B. Krishnappa]].
In 1988, at the age of 34, he became a member of the [[Karnataka Legislative Assembly]] and, in 2006, chairman of the [[Kannada Development Authority]], a post with Cabinet rank that he held until 2008.
He has been head of the Department of Kannada at [[Bangalore University]] and a member of the University Syndicate of [[Kannada University]], Hampi. He is acknowledged as a symbol of the [[Dalit movement]] and a leading public intellectual and Kannada poet.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Satyanarayana and Tharu|title=From those Stubs Steel Nibs are Sprouting: New Dalit Writing from South India Vol II|date=2013|publisher=Harper Collins India|location=New Delhi|isbn=978-93-5029-376-8|pages=151–155}}</ref>
== Bibliography == * ''Holemadigara Haadu'' (Songs of the [[Holeya]] and [[Madiga]], 1975) * ''Saaviraaru Nadigalu'' (Thousands of Rivers, 1979) * ''Kappu Kaadina Haadu'' (The Song of the Black Forest, 1982) * ''Aayda Kavithegalu'' (Selected Poems, 1997) * ''Meravanige'' (Procession, 2000) * ''Nanna Janagalu mattu Itara Kavitegalu'' (My People and Other Poems, 2005) * ''Ooru Keri: Atmakathana'' (1997) * ''Ooru, Keri 2: Atmakathana'' (2006) * ''[https://books.google.co.in/books?id=7ENOnADOlncC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Ooru+Keri+-+An+Autobiography&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CB4Q6AEwAGoVChMIpe2r2sKLxgIVw6ymCh0_BAAC#v=onepage&q=Ooru%20Keri%20-%20An%20Autobiography&f=false Ooru Keri - An Autobiography]'' ([[Sahitya Akademi]], 2003) * ''A Word With You, World: The Autobiography of a Poet'' ([[Navayana (publishing house)|Navayana]], 2013) Translated by S.R. Ramakrishna ([http://www.caravanmagazine.in/fiction/magadi-and-manchanabele Excerpt)] * [[K. Satyanarayana (academic)|Satyanarayana, K]] & [[Susie Tharu|Tharu, Susie]] (2013) ''From those Stubs Steel Nibs are Sprouting: New Dalit Writing from South Asia, Dossier 2: Kannada and Telugu'', New Delhi: HarperCollins India.
